b'<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>\n\n\n<!DOCTYPE workbook_page PUBLIC " -//Carnegie Mellon University//DTD Workbook Page MathML 3.8//EN" "http://oli.web.cmu.edu/dtd/oli_workbook_page_mathml_3_8.dtd">\n\n<workbook_page id="p6_collig_molar_mass" xmlns:cmd="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/content/metadata/2.1/"\n    xmlns:bib="http://bibtexml.sf.net/" xmlns:pref="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/preferences/"\n    xmlns:m="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" xmlns:theme="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/presentation/"\n    xmlns:wb="http://oli.web.cmu.edu/activity/workbook/">\n\n\n    <head>\n        <title>Determination of Molar Mass from Colligative Properties</title>\n        <objref idref="colligative_molar_mass"/>\n\n    </head>\n\n    <body>\n\n        <p>Osmotic pressure and changes in freezing point, boiling point, and vapor pressure are\n            directly proportional to the concentration of solute present. Consequently, we can use a\n            measurement of one of these properties to determine the molar mass of the solute from\n            the measurements.</p>\n        <example>\n            <p>A solution of 4.00 g of a nonelectrolyte dissolved in 55.0 g of benzene is found to\n                freeze at 2.32 \xc2\xb0C. What is the molar mass of this compound?</p>\n            <p>Determine the change in freezing point from the observed freezing point and the\n                freezing point of pure benzene.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\triangle T_\\mathrm f\\;=\\;5.5\\;^\\circ\\mathrm C\\;-\\;2.32\\;^\\circ\\mathrm\n                C\\;=\\;3.2\\;^\\circ\\mathrm C$$</formula>\n            <p>Determine the molal concentration from Kf, the freezing point depression constant for\n                benzene (Table), and \xce\x94Tf.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\begin{array}{l}\\triangle T_\\mathrm f\\;=\\;K_\\mathrm f\\mathrm\n                m\\\\m\\;=\\frac{\\;\\triangle T_\\mathrm f}{K_\\mathrm fm}\\;=\\;\\frac{3.2\\;^\\circ\\mathrm\n                C}{5.12\\;^\\circ\\mathrm C\\mathit\\;m^{-1}}\\;=\\;0.63\\;m\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            <p>Determine the number of moles of compound in the solution from the molal\n                concentration and the mass of solvent used to make the solution.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\mathrm{Moles}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;\\mathrm{solute}\\;=\\;\\frac{0.63\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;\\mathrm{solute}}{1.00\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm{kg}\\;\\mathrm{solvent}}}\\;\\times\\;0.0550\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{kg}\\;\\mathrm{solvent}}\\;=\\;0.035\\;\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n            <p>Determine the molar mass from the mass of the solute and the number of moles in that\n                mass.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{Molar}\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;=\\;\\frac{4.00\\;\\mathrm\n                g}{0.035\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;110\\;\\mathrm g/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="collig_mm_lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"/>\n             <example>\n            <p>A 0.500 L sample of an aqueous solution containing 10.0 g of hemoglobin has an\n                osmotic pressure of 5.9 torr at 22 \xc2\xb0C. What is the molar mass of hemoglobin?</p>\n            <p>Convert the osmotic pressure to atmospheres, then determine the molar concentration\n                from the osmotic pressure.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\begin{array}{l}\\Pi\\;=\\;5.9\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{torr}}\\;\\times\\;\\frac{1\\;\\mathrm{atm}}{760\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm{torr}}}\\;=\\;7.8\\times10^{-3}\\;\\mathrm{atm}\\\\\\Pi\\;=\\;MRT\\\\M\\;=\\;\\frac\\Pi{RT\\;}\\;=\\;\\frac{7.8\\times10^{-3}\\;\\mathrm{atm}}{(0.08206\\;\\mathrm\n                L\\cdot\\mathrm{atm}/\\mathrm{mol}\\cdot\\mathrm K)(295\\;\\mathrm\n                K)}\\;=\\;3.2\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm M\\end{array}$$</formula>\n            <p>Determine the number of moles of hemoglobin in the solution from the concentration\n                and the volume of the solution.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\require{cancel}\\mathrm{moles}\\;\\mathrm{of}\\;\\mathrm{hemoglobin}\\;=\\;\\frac{3.2\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm{mol}}{1\\cancel{\\;\\mathrm\n                L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}}\\;\\times\\;0.500\\;\\cancel{\\mathrm\n                L\\;\\mathrm{solution}}\\;=\\;1.6\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm{mol}\\;$$</formula>\n            <p>Determine the molar mass from the mass of hemoglobin and the number of moles in that\n                mass.</p>\n            <formula>$$\\mathrm{molar}\\;\\mathrm{mass}\\;=\\;\\frac{10.0\\;\\mathrm\n                g}{1.6\\times10^{-4}\\;\\mathrm{mol}}\\;=\\;6.2\\times10^4\\;\\mathrm\n                g/\\mathrm{mol}$$</formula>\n        </example>\n        <wb:inline idref="mm_collig_2lbd" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        <wb:inline idref="mm_collig_lbd3" purpose="learnbydoing"></wb:inline>\n        <wb:inline idref="mm_collig_digt" purpose="didigetthis"></wb:inline>\n        <p>Adapted from <link href="https://cnx.org/contents/havxkyvS@9.422:b39avmGq@29/Preface"\n            >Openstax Chemistry</link> under  <link\n                href="https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/4.0/"> Creative Commons Attribution\n                4.0 License. </link></p>\n        <p>Download for free at <link\n            href="http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312"\n            >http://cnx.org/contents/85abf193-2bd2-4908-8563-90b8a7ac8df6@9.312.</link></p>\n        \n\n    </body>\n</workbook_page>\n'